WEBVTT

00:06.832 --> 00:16.712
[♪♪♪]

00:34.512 --> 00:44.392
[♪♪♪]

01:07.893 --> 01:12.115
INTERVIEWER:
Mr. Lansky, why are the
American authorities after you?

01:12.159 --> 01:14.378
Well, apparently some
newspaper man wrote

01:14.422 --> 01:17.120
that I had $300 million.

01:17.164 --> 01:17.947
INTERVIEWER:
Is it true?

01:17.990 --> 01:19.296
[Lansky chuckles]

01:19.340 --> 01:22.430
I wish I had a million dollars.

01:22.473 --> 01:24.606
They accuse me
of making a president.

01:24.649 --> 01:26.651
Now, I don't know Mr. Nixon
any more

01:26.695 --> 01:29.001
than what I've read
in the newspapers.

01:29.045 --> 01:32.396
They claim I have 50%
of Lebanon casinos,

01:32.440 --> 01:34.311
50% of Monte Carlo.

01:34.355 --> 01:37.227
Now how ridiculous
can we really get?

01:37.271 --> 01:38.707
INTERVIEWER:
Mr. Lansky, is there such
a thing

01:38.750 --> 01:40.491
as organized crime?

01:45.670 --> 01:47.933
I have no knowledge
on the subject.

01:47.977 --> 01:49.805
[♪♪♪]

01:59.293 --> 02:01.251
DAVID: [Voice-over]
Listen Eva,
I'm in Florida, honey.

02:01.295 --> 02:03.297
Daddy's here for work.

02:03.340 --> 02:05.081
- What do they have here?
- [Chuckles]

02:05.125 --> 02:08.780
They have oranges and gators
and Mickey Mouse.

02:08.824 --> 02:10.826
Next time we can go
and I promise.

02:12.436 --> 02:14.699
Okay Eva,
can you put your momma on?

02:18.268 --> 02:20.314
Christie, Christie,
Christie please?

02:20.357 --> 02:22.751
I know that the check bounced.

02:22.794 --> 02:23.839
Okay, but that's OK.

02:23.882 --> 02:24.970
That's why I'm in Miami.

02:25.014 --> 02:27.147
I'm going to do some book
signings.

02:27.190 --> 02:28.278
Yeah, sure they gotta.

02:28.322 --> 02:30.628
They are putting me
in a fancy hotel,

02:30.672 --> 02:31.803
they gonna give me the--

02:34.502 --> 02:37.505
Christie, I know
my responsibilities, alright?

02:39.246 --> 02:42.379
Look Christie, I'm trying
my best, alright?

02:42.423 --> 02:43.467
Trying my best.

02:43.511 --> 02:53.434
[♪♪♪]

04:03.591 --> 04:13.514
[♪♪♪]

04:19.563 --> 04:20.477
David Stone.

04:20.521 --> 04:21.913
Mr. Lansky, it's a pleasure.

04:21.957 --> 04:23.132
How was your trip?

04:23.175 --> 04:24.960
Fine, thanks, umm.

04:25.003 --> 04:25.961
Hope you don't mind,
I got a coffee.

04:26.004 --> 04:27.789
You mind sitting down there?

04:27.832 --> 04:30.835
Huh, yeah sure.

04:30.879 --> 04:32.141
Thank you.

04:35.623 --> 04:38.582
Hello, Mr. Lansky, how are you?

04:38.626 --> 04:40.715
Fine, Daphne.

04:40.758 --> 04:42.107
How's your mother feel?

04:42.151 --> 04:44.893
Ah, good days and bad, you know.

04:44.936 --> 04:45.763
It is a mission.

04:45.807 --> 04:47.330
Yeah, I know all about that.

04:47.374 --> 04:48.549
What can I get for you, honey?

04:48.592 --> 04:50.812
We'll do a couple of them
sandwiches.

04:50.855 --> 04:54.119
Bills sliced and fatty cut
and an assortment of pickles.

04:54.163 --> 04:55.947
So, the usual.

04:55.991 --> 04:57.340
I'll pick out the best ones.

04:57.384 --> 04:58.428
OK.

05:00.822 --> 05:02.650
I'd like you to remove that.

05:05.392 --> 05:06.436
Ok.

05:08.395 --> 05:10.397
You're from Pittsburgh.

05:10.440 --> 05:13.965
You graduated on scholarship
with honors from Princeton.

05:14.009 --> 05:16.838
You were on the crime beat
at the Fort Wayne News Sentinel

05:16.881 --> 05:18.970
before you started
writing books.

05:19.014 --> 05:21.451
You've got a wife, Christina,
and two young children,

05:21.495 --> 05:23.453
Eva and Jack.

05:23.497 --> 05:27.414
I make it a point of knowing
who I associate myself with.

05:27.457 --> 05:30.982
Mr. Stone,
old business habits never die.

05:33.115 --> 05:36.727
It's a complicated thing,
isn't it, marriage, children.

05:43.430 --> 05:47.390
I've been reading some articles
about you.

05:47.434 --> 05:49.784
Forget all that.

05:49.827 --> 05:51.742
I'm here to tell you
the real story.

05:51.786 --> 05:53.048
[David chuckles]

05:53.091 --> 05:54.789
All right, well, that's great,
cause I'm-

05:54.832 --> 05:56.443
I'm here to write
the real story.

05:56.486 --> 05:59.707
Four packs a day, 60 years.

05:59.750 --> 06:02.623
I finally work up the courage
to quit.

06:02.666 --> 06:04.364
A week later,
I go to see my doctor.

06:04.407 --> 06:06.235
He tells me I'm dying.

06:06.278 --> 06:08.063
[Lansky laughs]

06:08.106 --> 06:10.674
As a writer, I thought you would
appreciate the irony in that.

06:10.718 --> 06:12.807
I do. I'm just I'm very sorry
to hear that.

06:12.850 --> 06:15.766
My circumstances offer me
the privilege

06:15.810 --> 06:18.116
to pick who I want
to tell my story.

06:18.160 --> 06:20.031
Your book on Kennedy paid
you well?

06:20.075 --> 06:21.468
Well, I did OK.

06:21.511 --> 06:25.863
It's been a few years since
lady luck visited you.

06:25.907 --> 06:27.909
Yeah well history doesn't
always repeat itself.

06:29.954 --> 06:31.434
When I was a young boy,

06:31.478 --> 06:34.481
I spent my days
at the public library.

06:34.524 --> 06:36.047
I read everything

06:36.091 --> 06:40.225
and I have a particular interest
in history.

06:40.269 --> 06:44.186
People see the same thing
from different perspectives,

06:44.229 --> 06:46.797
and that fascinates me.

06:46.841 --> 06:48.669
But what do you want from this?

06:48.712 --> 06:52.673
Why does David still want to
write a book about Meyer Lansky?

06:52.716 --> 06:54.370
Oh.

06:59.767 --> 07:02.857
Everything that I've read
in history about you says

07:02.900 --> 07:04.293
you're a complicated man

07:04.336 --> 07:06.948
and maybe I like stories about
complicated people.

07:06.991 --> 07:11.735
And I think that your story,
the real story.

07:11.779 --> 07:12.997
I don't think
he's been told yet,

07:13.041 --> 07:14.521
and I don't think
it's about one man,

07:14.564 --> 07:16.218
I think
it's about the 20th century.

07:19.134 --> 07:20.875
That was quite a speech,

07:20.918 --> 07:22.529
but you didn't answer
the question.

07:24.835 --> 07:25.836
I need the money.

07:25.880 --> 07:30.362
Ah, there it is, the truth.

07:30.406 --> 07:32.930
When I die,
the book is yours to sell.

07:32.974 --> 07:36.194
Until then, you won't show
the manuscript to no one.

07:36.238 --> 07:39.284
Anything I choose to tell you
is off the record

07:39.328 --> 07:42.418
until I give you permission
to put it in the book.

07:42.462 --> 07:45.029
Without my approval, what you
have is a work of fiction.

07:45.073 --> 07:47.379
- I won't incriminate myself.
- OK.

07:47.423 --> 07:49.469
Any conversations
you have about me

07:49.512 --> 07:51.122
outside of our meetings,

07:51.166 --> 07:52.559
- I want to know.
- Sure.

07:52.602 --> 07:57.999
Betray me
and there will be consequences.

07:58.042 --> 07:59.653
Are these terms
are agreeable to you?

08:01.742 --> 08:03.178
Yes sir.

08:05.572 --> 08:08.531
I hope our collaboration
will be a successful one.

08:11.708 --> 08:14.450
[typewriter keys clicking]

08:37.473 --> 08:38.343
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
Hello?

08:38.387 --> 08:40.215
Hey, Christie, it's me.

08:40.258 --> 08:43.044
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
Hey, it's ok baby,
mommy's got you.

08:43.087 --> 08:45.220
You OK?

08:45.263 --> 08:46.874
You don't sound, OK?

08:46.917 --> 08:48.440
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
No, I'm not.

08:48.484 --> 08:50.486
Jack's got a 103 and he's not
holding his spoon down.

08:50.530 --> 08:52.227
Take him to a doctor.

08:52.270 --> 08:54.925
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
Excuse me?
I took him to the doctor.

08:54.969 --> 08:56.666
Listen, I can't do this, OK?
Not now.

08:56.710 --> 09:00.452
Christie, I gotta chance
to write a new book, alright?

09:00.496 --> 09:01.628
And it could be-

09:01.671 --> 09:02.585
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
Oh, David, no.

09:02.629 --> 09:04.631
Could be something really good.

09:04.674 --> 09:06.589
CHRISTIE: [on phone]
Oh David,
I called your publisher.

09:06.633 --> 09:08.591
They had no idea
you were even in Miami,

09:08.635 --> 09:10.637
which means
you are lying to me.

09:10.680 --> 09:12.073
I can't go through this,
I've got to go.

09:13.422 --> 09:16.120
[Phone hangs up]

09:16.164 --> 09:26.043
[♪♪♪]

09:28.829 --> 09:31.745
LANSKY:
You said you read some stories
about me in the papers.

09:31.788 --> 09:34.617
My reputation has a habit
of preceding me.

09:34.661 --> 09:37.272
When they don't know you
they put labels on you,

09:37.315 --> 09:39.840
Master Stock Manipulator.

09:39.883 --> 09:43.887
America's most successful
casino operator in history.

09:43.931 --> 09:45.628
Mob's accountant.

09:45.672 --> 09:48.022
The feds even leaked the story
to the press

09:48.065 --> 09:51.634
about me having
$300 million squirreled away.

09:51.678 --> 09:52.853
[Lansky laughs]

09:52.896 --> 09:54.724
If you find out
who's out there guessing,

09:54.768 --> 09:56.334
please be sure to let me know.

09:56.378 --> 09:57.553
- Yeah.
- You don't get to keep it,

09:57.597 --> 09:59.294
call me
and I'll give you a piece.

09:59.337 --> 10:00.730
- Fair enough.
- [Lansky laughs]

10:00.774 --> 10:02.776
The labels are the accurate?

10:02.819 --> 10:05.387
It's your book.
You decide.

10:05.430 --> 10:06.562
OK, alright.

10:06.606 --> 10:07.650
[Lansky laughs]

10:07.694 --> 10:09.217
Okay.

10:09.260 --> 10:13.003
You strike me as a rather
obsequious guy, David.

10:13.047 --> 10:14.222
[Chuckles]

10:14.265 --> 10:15.745
Quick to please.

10:15.789 --> 10:17.355
Never thought of myself
that way.

10:17.399 --> 10:18.792
- You're seperated.
- Hmm.

10:18.835 --> 10:20.620
What did your wife
think about that?

10:20.663 --> 10:23.492
Did she find you that way?

10:23.535 --> 10:24.885
We're here to talk about you.

10:24.928 --> 10:26.408
We are not here
to talk about me, Mr. Lansky.

10:26.451 --> 10:29.541
No, no, no. We have to talk
about you and me.

10:31.413 --> 10:33.894
- You know, I was married also.
- Yeah?

10:33.937 --> 10:35.460
Yeah, twice.

10:38.202 --> 10:39.334
You know, what they say,

10:39.377 --> 10:40.944
can't live with them,
can't shoot them.

10:40.988 --> 10:42.946
[David chuckles]

10:44.513 --> 10:46.297
So where do we start?

10:46.341 --> 10:48.386
Let's start
when you were a child.

10:48.430 --> 10:50.737
Russia.

10:50.780 --> 10:52.869
The only thing
I remember about Russia,

10:52.913 --> 10:56.046
is one day me and my uncle
crossing a path

10:56.090 --> 10:57.744
and some Cossacks
ordered my uncle

10:57.787 --> 10:59.702
to open his potato sack.

10:59.746 --> 11:01.922
And toss a potato up
in the air.

11:01.965 --> 11:03.010
My Uncle obeyed.

11:05.534 --> 11:07.710
Tossed a potato into the air,

11:07.754 --> 11:11.801
and the Cossack takes out this
fucking sword and swoosh.

11:14.064 --> 11:16.719
He wasn't aiming
for the potatoe.

11:16.763 --> 11:19.679
He was aiming
for my uncle's hands,

11:19.722 --> 11:20.984
Cut it right off.

11:21.028 --> 11:22.116
Tough guys.

11:22.159 --> 11:25.336
But swords,
we didn't have a sword.

11:25.380 --> 11:26.686
That was the difference.

11:28.165 --> 11:29.732
I never forgot that.

11:31.342 --> 11:35.172
I promised myself I'd never
be that helpless again.

11:35.216 --> 11:39.046
The next time I'll be the one
holding the knife.

11:39.089 --> 11:41.309
That's the only thing Russia
ever gave me,

11:41.352 --> 11:42.963
when I swore that day.

11:45.313 --> 11:48.142
Made me stronger,
it sharpened me.

11:53.582 --> 11:55.758
I wish I knew where that
cocksucker was today,

11:55.802 --> 11:58.848
I'll show them
what a tough guy he is.

11:58.892 --> 12:01.503
The real story starts
in America.

12:06.813 --> 12:10.338
LANSKY: [Voice-over]
By the time I was 10,
I was sharp as a shiv.

12:10.381 --> 12:14.690
My mind was my escape
and more than anything, numbers.

12:14.734 --> 12:16.910
Numbers gave my world
some order.

12:16.953 --> 12:19.303
And if a kid with that kind
of interest in numbers,

12:19.347 --> 12:22.742
there was nothing as thrilling
is a dice game.

12:22.785 --> 12:24.308
I would watch them play.

12:24.352 --> 12:27.181
But oh boy, my old man found out
that was how

12:27.224 --> 12:29.313
I was spending my time,

12:29.357 --> 12:30.793
My father?

12:30.837 --> 12:32.795
Everything he did,
he did for us.

12:32.839 --> 12:35.232
He was an honest man
earning an honest living.

12:35.276 --> 12:36.103
There's nothing wrong with that.

12:36.146 --> 12:38.540
He wasn't living his life.

12:38.583 --> 12:40.411
His life was living him.

12:40.455 --> 12:41.630
I guess that's what we do.

12:41.673 --> 12:45.416
We measure ourselves
against our fathers.

12:45.460 --> 12:47.331
And you?
What was your's like?

12:49.464 --> 12:51.161
My father died when I was young.

12:52.989 --> 12:54.599
That must have been hard.

12:58.429 --> 13:01.824
So being an honest man.
Being an honest father.

13:01.868 --> 13:04.087
Yeah.

13:04.131 --> 13:05.306
Is that beneath you?

13:08.396 --> 13:11.355
What I know is that
life wouldn't wait for me.

13:11.399 --> 13:18.188
[♪♪♪]

13:18.232 --> 13:21.539
LANSKY: [Voice-over]
It all happened so fast,
I put down the nickel

13:21.583 --> 13:23.672
my mother gave me
to pick up some bread.

13:26.718 --> 13:29.852
In a matter of seconds,
my nickel was gone.

13:29.896 --> 13:32.463
Can you imagine having to tell
my mother and father

13:32.507 --> 13:34.074
why we couldn't eat
that night?

13:34.117 --> 13:37.773
He took your money
and you just felt ashamed.

13:37.817 --> 13:39.166
It was rage.

13:40.776 --> 13:43.692
You ever feel that, David?

13:43.735 --> 13:47.827
A rage so strong
it changes the path you're on?

13:47.870 --> 13:49.611
Never felt anything like that.

13:49.654 --> 13:51.831
There are people
in this world who will try to

13:51.874 --> 13:55.312
make you believe that
they are better than you,

13:55.356 --> 13:58.446
that they can win
at your expense.

13:58.489 --> 14:03.320
Rage is a tool we use to look
those people in the eye

14:03.364 --> 14:04.844
and prove them wrong.

14:04.887 --> 14:06.410
That's what drove you to win
at dice?

14:06.454 --> 14:09.674
It did much more than drive me
to win.

14:09.718 --> 14:11.589
It drove me to control the game.

14:15.724 --> 14:18.422
LANSKY: [Voice-over]
I calculated the odds
and payoffs.

14:18.466 --> 14:21.686
Watched how the probabilities
ebbed and flowed,

14:21.730 --> 14:23.688
but something didn't make sense.

14:23.732 --> 14:26.126
I knew something was going on,

14:26.169 --> 14:29.303
something invisible
that no one else could see.

14:29.346 --> 14:31.000
And then I saw it.

14:37.964 --> 14:41.924
A blink of the eye,
a scratch of the air,

14:41.968 --> 14:45.145
I figured out what these guys
were doing,

14:45.188 --> 14:46.842
they rigged the game.

14:46.886 --> 14:48.931
It was the outsider.

14:48.975 --> 14:51.586
He was the one
controlling the game.

14:54.110 --> 14:55.720
And isn't that what we all want,
David?

14:56.939 --> 14:59.637
The only one is in gambling,
as in life,

14:59.681 --> 15:01.465
are those who control the game.

15:14.609 --> 15:17.438
[Music playing in distance]

15:36.413 --> 15:40.852
I think that you have the smile
of a beauty queen, right?

15:40.896 --> 15:44.204
I do know I don't think that
they stick out.

15:44.247 --> 15:48.251
I don't think that
there's a huge gap, but,

15:48.295 --> 15:49.600
if you think they're going to
straighten out,

15:49.644 --> 15:51.689
then what's the point
of getting braces, right?

15:51.733 --> 15:53.430
EVA: [on phone]
Mom's right.

15:53.474 --> 15:54.997
Right about what?

15:55.041 --> 15:56.520
EVA: [on phone]
We can't afford it.

15:56.564 --> 15:59.480
That's why you don't want me
to get braces.

15:59.523 --> 16:03.919
She say that?
Put your mama on, Eva? Hmm?

16:03.963 --> 16:05.486
EVA: [on phone]
She said she can't talk.

16:05.529 --> 16:07.183
What ya mean she can't talk?

16:07.227 --> 16:09.533
If she can't talk
or she won't talk?

16:09.577 --> 16:12.710
EVA: [on phone]
She said she's not talking
to you, daddy.

16:12.754 --> 16:14.016
Give mama a message, alright?

16:14.060 --> 16:15.496
- Can you do that?
- Okay.

16:15.539 --> 16:17.933
And you tell her that the reason
that Daddy's in Miami

16:17.977 --> 16:19.891
is because of a man
called Meyer Lansky.

16:19.935 --> 16:20.980
EVA: [on phone]
Meyor Lasky?

16:21.023 --> 16:22.720
It's okay, she know who that is.

16:22.764 --> 16:26.028
And you tell her that
Mr. Lansky

16:26.072 --> 16:29.249
hired daddy personally to
write a book about his life.

16:29.292 --> 16:30.728
And every publisher
is going to want it

16:30.772 --> 16:32.339
and it's going to be best
selling when it is,

16:32.382 --> 16:36.299
daddy is gonna set your smile,
alright?

16:36.343 --> 16:37.474
EVA: [on phone]
OK.

16:37.518 --> 16:40.260
Because that's what daddies do.
Yeah?

16:40.303 --> 16:42.740
- Yeah.
-OK.

16:42.784 --> 16:45.047
Don't you worry
about your thing.

16:45.091 --> 16:46.353
Alright, you go tell her.

16:46.396 --> 16:47.397
EVA: [on phone]
I love you, daddy.

16:47.441 --> 16:48.529
Alright, bye.

16:55.492 --> 16:56.537
Sorry.

17:01.846 --> 17:03.544
You look like hell.

17:03.587 --> 17:06.025
Yeah, I didn't get much sleep.

17:09.506 --> 17:11.117
Problems at home?

17:14.250 --> 17:15.730
OK, umm.

17:19.908 --> 17:20.778
Ok, today--

17:20.822 --> 17:22.650
These problems you're having,

17:22.693 --> 17:25.740
I hope they're not interfering
with your ability to work.

17:25.783 --> 17:29.526
I'm here. I'm fine.

17:29.570 --> 17:30.701
Good.

17:34.662 --> 17:36.098
I want to talk
about Bugsy Siegel.

17:36.142 --> 17:38.666
It's Ben Siegel.

17:38.709 --> 17:40.842
Say that name again.

17:40.885 --> 17:43.714
DAVID: [Voice-over]
Ben Siegel, Bugsy.

17:43.758 --> 17:46.108
He and Lansky had bootlegging
and gambling racket

17:46.152 --> 17:48.241
known as
the Bugs and Meyer Gang.

17:48.284 --> 17:50.417
There were more than partners.

17:50.460 --> 17:52.027
They were like brothers.

17:52.071 --> 17:53.724
Lansky handle the numbers.

17:53.768 --> 17:55.509
Bugsy was the muscle.

17:55.552 --> 17:56.510
All right, Ben.

17:56.553 --> 17:58.903
- [Groaning]
- Come on.

17:58.947 --> 18:01.123
I think he gets to a point.

18:01.167 --> 18:02.516
DAVID: [Voice-over]
The only thing Bugsy enjoyed
more than killing

18:02.559 --> 18:04.866
was the ladies.

18:04.909 --> 18:06.607
Or maybe it was the other way
around.

18:17.531 --> 18:19.141
Luciano is looking for somebody

18:19.185 --> 18:21.012
to run as his transportation
for him.

18:23.232 --> 18:26.844
We offer Lucky
a deal on his distribution

18:26.888 --> 18:30.065
too favorable to turn down.

18:30.109 --> 18:32.154
Maybe we take a loss on it.

18:32.198 --> 18:33.199
[Ben chuckles]

18:34.417 --> 18:36.419
A loss?
How's that makes sense?

18:36.463 --> 18:39.901
We'll be getting in on the
ground up with Lucky Luciano

18:39.944 --> 18:42.077
and it will supply liquor
for our own operation

18:42.121 --> 18:43.513
at the same time.

18:43.557 --> 18:46.516
Profit margins are justified
tenfold.

18:49.345 --> 18:50.477
I did the math for you.

18:50.520 --> 18:51.608
Yeah, I'm sure you did.

18:51.652 --> 18:55.482
[Laughter]

18:55.525 --> 18:57.136
What do you think of that guy,
Ramsie?

18:57.179 --> 18:58.702
He's friendly.

18:58.746 --> 19:00.617
Gets along with the clientele,
why?

19:00.661 --> 19:03.272
He should lose the ring.

19:03.316 --> 19:05.666
It's distracting.

19:05.709 --> 19:07.450
Sends the wrong message.

19:10.845 --> 19:12.412
Rosen why are you
so fucking happy?

19:12.455 --> 19:15.676
LANSKY: [Voice-over]
Our operation
was expanding fast.

19:15.719 --> 19:18.113
We had to keep
our books clean,

19:18.157 --> 19:21.247
keep the authorities
off the money trail.

19:21.290 --> 19:24.467
If you're on a leaky boat,
you plug the holes.

19:24.511 --> 19:26.904
You over by 200.

19:26.948 --> 19:28.341
It was a good day
at the track.

19:28.384 --> 19:31.692
Yeah?
Explain the numbers to me.

19:34.303 --> 19:41.963
Uh, I had 9,320 on the seven
at--

19:42.006 --> 19:45.619
573 against the favorite.

19:45.662 --> 19:48.578
But you heard Reenam Roll
was a winner.

19:48.622 --> 19:51.538
So you, what?
You to sweeten the pot?

19:51.581 --> 19:56.151
You got to admit it.
He is good.

19:56.195 --> 19:59.459
Yeah, well, I couldn't lose.

19:59.502 --> 20:03.158
What did I tell you?
Trust your memory.

20:03.202 --> 20:07.815
I know, I just got a lot
of numbers to remember.

20:07.858 --> 20:12.167
You know, how many gambling
rooms I run in this town?

20:12.211 --> 20:16.650
The fact that you don't know
puts us at an advantage.

20:16.693 --> 20:18.434
You also got no idea
how much money

20:18.478 --> 20:22.177
comes through that door
each day, do you?

20:22.221 --> 20:23.396
You know what?

20:23.439 --> 20:26.877
The only one who knows is me

20:26.921 --> 20:31.839
and I keep that number
in my head.

20:31.882 --> 20:35.799
But you do know the percentage
of our bets don't you?

20:35.843 --> 20:39.542
- 10%.
- 10% win or lose?

20:39.586 --> 20:42.980
That's what sustains
this business, Jimmy.

20:43.024 --> 20:45.156
Is there anything else
you want to tell us?

20:45.200 --> 20:47.594
Who else is gambling
with our money, maybe?

20:47.637 --> 20:50.684
I swear, Bugsy,
I don't know nothing.

20:53.687 --> 20:55.645
Did you just call me Bugsy.

20:59.432 --> 21:03.349
Everybody calls you that,
at least when you're not around.

21:06.482 --> 21:11.270
Well, now I'm confused.

21:11.313 --> 21:13.750
Am I not standing here?

21:13.794 --> 21:15.404
What am I?

21:15.448 --> 21:17.711
Am I a figment
of your imagination?

21:17.754 --> 21:19.016
No.

21:19.060 --> 21:20.757
No, no, because that's
what you just said.

21:20.801 --> 21:24.065
That's what people call me
when I'm not around.

21:24.108 --> 21:26.415
But I'm right here.

21:26.459 --> 21:30.201
Meyer, do you see me?

21:30.245 --> 21:31.812
I see you, Bennie.

21:34.423 --> 21:36.295
I'm going to ask you
one more time, Jimmy.

21:40.516 --> 21:42.910
Is there anything else
you want to tell us?

21:44.172 --> 21:46.305
- No, I--
- Don't lie to me.

21:52.354 --> 21:54.400
Don't forget to breathe.

21:54.443 --> 21:56.706
They say breathing is good.

21:56.750 --> 21:58.055
Okay.

21:59.535 --> 22:03.452
Now, don't you want me to know?

22:05.802 --> 22:13.984
I-I-I may have heard something
about a dealer

22:14.028 --> 22:16.422
at your Roma at Allen.

22:16.465 --> 22:18.554
I don't remember his name.

22:18.598 --> 22:20.077
Well, let me jog your memory,
huh?

22:22.602 --> 22:26.519
Ow! Rosen, his name is Rosen.

22:26.562 --> 22:28.477
Now what exactly
did he tell you?

22:28.521 --> 22:30.871
He was tipping off some players.

22:30.914 --> 22:33.526
I don't know anything else,
I swear.

22:36.267 --> 22:38.618
Sit up.

22:38.661 --> 22:39.967
Thank you, Jimmy.

22:41.490 --> 22:44.363
It's very helpful for us,
you know.

22:44.406 --> 22:49.063
Oh, at least you die
with a clean conscience, right?

22:49.106 --> 22:50.456
Who?

22:50.499 --> 22:52.980
- You.
- [Gunshot]

22:53.023 --> 22:56.636
YOUNG LANSKY:
God dammit, not in my ear.

22:56.679 --> 23:04.034
[♪♪♪]

23:04.078 --> 23:07.037
CHARLIE:
First time me and you met
and here comes little Meyer

23:07.081 --> 23:10.345
walking through the snow
like the wandering Jew.

23:10.389 --> 23:11.781
And my guys, I mean,

23:11.825 --> 23:13.174
there must've been like
six of us or something, huh?

23:13.217 --> 23:14.218
Seven.

23:14.262 --> 23:15.219
We ask him
to empty his pockets,

23:15.263 --> 23:16.830
if he wants to cross the street,

23:16.873 --> 23:20.355
YOUNG LANSKY:
Ask?
I don't recall any asking.

23:20.399 --> 23:23.445
We politely instructed him
to remove the contents

23:23.489 --> 23:25.447
of his pockets.

23:25.491 --> 23:27.275
DAVID: [Voice-over]
Charlie Lucky Luciano,

23:27.318 --> 23:29.451
father of modern
organized crime.

23:29.495 --> 23:31.279
He created the governing body
of the Mafia

23:31.322 --> 23:32.411
known as The Commission

23:32.454 --> 23:34.804
and the National
Crime Syndicate,

23:34.848 --> 23:38.155
Confederation of Italian, Jewish
and Irish Gangsters.

23:38.199 --> 23:40.331
And you know
what he said to us?

23:40.375 --> 23:43.726
"Go fuck yourselves,
you guinea bastards."

23:43.770 --> 23:47.121
That's right and the balls
on this one, huh?

23:47.164 --> 23:48.905
[Lansky chuckles]

23:48.949 --> 23:51.560
This kid would fought all six
of us before giving up a penny.

23:51.604 --> 23:52.692
So what do I do?

23:52.735 --> 23:54.520
I let them go.

23:54.563 --> 23:57.087
Kid as us fearlessness as that
deserves to be rewarded.

23:58.654 --> 24:00.482
How many times I've gotta hear
this story, huh, Lucky?

24:00.526 --> 24:03.616
Eh, this story is like wine,
Benny.

24:03.659 --> 24:05.661
Get's better with age.

24:05.705 --> 24:07.010
I prefer whiskey.

24:07.054 --> 24:09.839
The point is.

24:09.883 --> 24:15.062
You and me, Meyer, Italian, Jew,
none of that matters.

24:15.105 --> 24:17.978
What matters is the way
we see the world.

24:18.021 --> 24:20.241
We fight our way in
from the outside.

24:20.284 --> 24:21.721
That's right.

24:21.764 --> 24:25.768
This distribution business
you proposing,

24:25.812 --> 24:27.466
we got ourselves a deal.

24:29.685 --> 24:32.035
I'll drink to that.

24:32.079 --> 24:32.949
[Speaks Hebrew]

24:40.130 --> 24:42.742
See that half-Checz girl?

24:42.785 --> 24:45.484
You know, she's jotting
everything down.

24:45.527 --> 24:49.705
Who's coming, who's going,
who's talking to who?

24:49.749 --> 24:54.754
That all goes to lucky.
It's the attention to detail.

24:54.797 --> 24:59.193
That's what makes a Lucky,
Lucky.

24:59.236 --> 25:02.239
I'm paying attention
to a different detail.

25:02.283 --> 25:03.632
Be right back.

25:03.676 --> 25:13.555
[♪♪♪]

25:15.426 --> 25:16.602
YOUNG BEN:
Have a seat.

25:19.518 --> 25:20.649
This is my friend, Meyer.

25:20.693 --> 25:24.218
Meyer, please meet
Anne and Louise.

25:24.261 --> 25:25.393
Hello.

25:29.615 --> 25:30.877
YOUNG BEN:
Now tell me something,
what are two lovely ladies

25:30.920 --> 25:33.836
like yourself doing
in a place like this?

25:33.880 --> 25:36.535
The sign outside said
it was a drugstore.

25:36.578 --> 25:38.014
I needed some toothpaste.

25:40.843 --> 25:42.323
So what are you guys,

25:42.366 --> 25:44.499
professional gamblers
or something?

25:44.543 --> 25:48.590
Oh! Us? No. No, no, no.

25:48.634 --> 25:51.506
Then what line
of business are you in?

25:51.550 --> 25:53.116
Truck rentals.

25:53.160 --> 25:55.684
LOUISE:
Truck rentals?
What does that mean?

25:55.728 --> 25:58.469
Means we rent trucks.

25:58.513 --> 26:00.471
Anne, look.

26:00.515 --> 26:03.910
It's the big cheese gangster
from the newsreels.

26:03.953 --> 26:06.129
They say he murdered
his own cousin.

26:07.217 --> 26:08.828
Louise.

26:08.871 --> 26:12.483
YOUNG BEN:
Hey, how's about I go over
there tell them to

26:12.527 --> 26:14.834
come give you a good old kiss
on the lips.

26:14.877 --> 26:16.575
Very funny.

26:18.359 --> 26:19.578
OK.

26:23.494 --> 26:27.281
What the hell?
Is he really doing it?

26:27.324 --> 26:29.370
[Young Ben whispering]

26:29.413 --> 26:33.113
Oh, my God,
he's looking right at us.

26:33.156 --> 26:35.115
Let's get out of here.

26:35.158 --> 26:36.986
I'm not going anywhere.

26:39.162 --> 26:42.035
The man is a killer
and these guys are his friends.

26:45.342 --> 26:46.953
They seem harmless.

26:49.651 --> 26:51.305
Suit, yourself.

26:59.356 --> 27:03.317
So you're in the truck
rental business?

27:09.628 --> 27:10.803
Cold?

27:17.505 --> 27:18.724
You need a coat.

27:21.117 --> 27:23.250
Are you going to buy me one?

27:23.293 --> 27:25.121
[Young Lansky laughs]

27:30.300 --> 27:31.519
Fur.

27:35.001 --> 27:36.176
Mink.

27:38.744 --> 27:44.532
Leather trim
down to the knees.

27:48.754 --> 27:50.669
And what will you do
with the rest?

27:54.020 --> 27:55.151
Of this?

27:57.110 --> 28:01.331
This I'm going to keep
for our future.

28:07.337 --> 28:17.217
[♪♪♪]

28:29.011 --> 28:30.404
DAVID:
Not too cold.

28:33.886 --> 28:35.365
It's refreshing.

28:35.409 --> 28:39.587
Oh, it's cold.

28:39.630 --> 28:41.458
Alright, crazy.
Would you like 'em?

28:43.156 --> 28:44.810
Sure, why not.

28:47.029 --> 28:50.554
Thank you, I'm Maureen.

28:50.598 --> 28:51.773
I'm David.

28:56.256 --> 28:58.301
You're a writer.

28:58.345 --> 29:00.826
Yeah? How do you know that?

29:00.869 --> 29:02.392
I hear you taping at night?

29:02.436 --> 29:03.567
Yeah?

29:03.611 --> 29:05.439
Yeah.

29:05.482 --> 29:07.484
And the walls are pretty thin.

29:10.357 --> 29:12.576
Spy novels?

29:12.620 --> 29:14.056
I'm just doing research.

29:14.100 --> 29:15.666
On women in swimming pools?

29:18.321 --> 29:21.063
It's good you quick,
very quick.

29:24.066 --> 29:27.461
What about you?
Are you on vacation?

29:27.504 --> 29:28.810
Something like that.

29:32.945 --> 29:36.383
Doctor, are you telling us that
Buddy will have to wear a brace

29:36.426 --> 29:37.776
the rest of his life?

29:41.562 --> 29:43.738
If you'd like, I'd be happy
to recommend specialists

29:43.782 --> 29:45.305
who are developing
a new treatment

29:45.348 --> 29:46.480
for cerebral palsy.

29:46.523 --> 29:48.264
Answer the goddamn question.

29:51.528 --> 29:53.879
My professional opinion is,
you a--

29:54.967 --> 30:04.846
[♪♪♪]

30:04.890 --> 30:06.500
The doctor said
there was no chance

30:06.543 --> 30:08.458
he would ever be normal.

30:08.502 --> 30:11.157
And you couldn't accept that?

30:11.200 --> 30:14.508
I wasn't about to let my son
become weak and vulnerable.

30:14.551 --> 30:15.552
No.

30:16.989 --> 30:19.165
- [Laughs]
- And if I could help it.

30:19.208 --> 30:21.080
Why did that bother you so much?

30:21.123 --> 30:22.342
Why do you think?

30:29.740 --> 30:33.875
Would it not bother you to see
your own son go through his life

30:33.919 --> 30:35.311
at such a disadvantage?

30:37.836 --> 30:39.098
I couldn't accept the odds.

30:41.317 --> 30:42.405
The odds?

30:42.449 --> 30:44.668
It was a mathematical
equation,

30:44.712 --> 30:48.281
the proportion of those
afflicted versus those cured,

30:48.324 --> 30:49.978
the rate at which
those afflicted

30:50.022 --> 30:51.762
were able to walk again.

30:51.806 --> 30:53.025
I ran the numbers to my head.

30:53.068 --> 30:54.374
I made the calculations.

30:54.417 --> 30:56.724
You thought
you could beat the odds?

30:56.767 --> 30:57.681
Yes.

30:59.945 --> 31:01.903
What about faith?

31:01.947 --> 31:02.948
Faith?

31:02.991 --> 31:04.079
Mm hmm.

31:04.123 --> 31:05.254
Maybe God wanted him
to be like that.

31:05.298 --> 31:06.473
Who?

31:09.693 --> 31:15.482
Hello, God, hello,
hell fucking lo.

31:15.525 --> 31:17.527
I ain't hearing anybody
answer me.

31:17.571 --> 31:20.313
Maybe he's got nothing
he wants to tell you.

31:20.356 --> 31:23.882
And he made that clear,
didn't he?

31:27.711 --> 31:30.323
You OK?

31:30.366 --> 31:31.367
Let's do this.

31:31.411 --> 31:41.334
[♪♪♪]

31:43.249 --> 31:45.860
- [Groaning]
- Come on you.

31:45.904 --> 31:46.730
Shut up, Rosen..

31:46.774 --> 31:49.646
[Muffled shouting]

31:58.394 --> 32:00.875
Get down, come on, get down.

32:00.919 --> 32:04.270
Please, don't do anything
to him, please!

32:04.313 --> 32:06.489
Hey, hey, woah, woah, woah,
enough.

32:06.533 --> 32:08.056
Hey, what the fuck
is she doing here?

32:08.100 --> 32:09.318
Well you told me
to bring her down.

32:09.362 --> 32:11.973
MRS. ROSEN:
Please, please, he's a good man.

32:12.017 --> 32:12.887
He's a father.

32:12.931 --> 32:14.976
We have four children, please.

32:15.020 --> 32:16.021
Oh God.

32:16.064 --> 32:17.587
Get up.

32:17.631 --> 32:20.460
Here, this is for you.

32:20.503 --> 32:24.681
Your husband has been stealing
from me for years, Mrs. Rosen.

32:24.725 --> 32:27.467
A nickel at a time,
money that adds up.

32:27.510 --> 32:32.124
Mrs. Rosen, you knew about this,
didn't you?

32:33.212 --> 32:36.215
[Sobbing]

32:36.258 --> 32:37.216
It's OK.

32:42.743 --> 32:45.354
This is a warning.

32:45.398 --> 32:49.837
But if you ever mention what you
see here today to anyone.

32:49.880 --> 32:54.668
You'll be putting your life
and your children's in danger.

32:57.540 --> 33:01.240
You understand?

33:01.283 --> 33:02.589
Get her out of here.

33:05.461 --> 33:07.289
May I help you with anything,
Mrs. Rosen?

33:07.333 --> 33:09.074
Come on, deal with it.

33:12.077 --> 33:13.687
Don't worry about him,
he's okay.

33:17.082 --> 33:18.953
Where were you?

33:18.997 --> 33:22.913
She was a mess, boss.
I was trying to be delicate.

33:22.957 --> 33:28.745
Never let your emotions dictate
your actions ever again.

33:30.878 --> 33:33.750
[Mrs. Rosen crying]

33:37.189 --> 33:41.149
[Mr. Rosen muffled speech]

33:43.891 --> 33:45.806
[Crying]

33:53.335 --> 33:55.294
[Gunshot]

33:55.337 --> 34:03.302
[♪♪♪]

34:03.345 --> 34:06.348
[Crying]

34:06.392 --> 34:15.140
[♪♪♪]

34:24.845 --> 34:27.108
So you left them fatherless?

34:27.152 --> 34:28.370
Three children.

34:28.414 --> 34:31.678
He left them fatherless.

34:31.721 --> 34:33.984
Is that what you tell yourself,
so you can sleep at night?

34:34.028 --> 34:35.508
No, I don't have to tell myself
anything

34:35.551 --> 34:38.337
when I go to sleep at night.

34:38.380 --> 34:40.513
It's the way we live.
It's business.

34:42.863 --> 34:44.995
What do you want,
a fucking fairy tale, David?

34:45.039 --> 34:46.910
Go home and write a fairy tale.

34:48.434 --> 34:50.000
LANSKY: [on recording]
I want you to write
a book about me.

34:50.044 --> 34:52.525
Would that be
of interest to you?

34:52.568 --> 34:55.745
DAVID: [on recording]
Yeah, I'd be very interested
in that.

34:55.789 --> 34:58.574
LANSKY: [on recording]
Good, I'll need you to come
to Miami.

34:58.618 --> 35:01.142
There's a coffee shop not far
from where I live.

35:01.186 --> 35:03.188
Take down this address.

35:03.231 --> 35:05.277
Okay?

35:05.320 --> 35:07.105
We need more resources.

35:07.148 --> 35:11.065
Even after sell him Frank?
15 years.

35:11.109 --> 35:12.545
You got all the surveillance
you asked for.

35:12.588 --> 35:14.112
What else are you expecting
to find here?

35:14.155 --> 35:17.767
The $300 million that
Lansky has stashed away.

35:17.811 --> 35:19.900
This guy, Stone, can really
open the door for us.

35:19.943 --> 35:21.815
Opening the door?

35:21.858 --> 35:24.209
There are no more doors to open,
Frank,

35:24.252 --> 35:28.300
tax evasion, contempt of court,
they threw it all away.

35:28.343 --> 35:30.780
And no indictment.

35:30.824 --> 35:32.652
Lansky's impenetrable.

35:32.695 --> 35:35.045
But that stuff was 10 years ago.

35:35.089 --> 35:37.178
And where's he been
for the last 10 years?

35:37.222 --> 35:40.181
Federal prison?
No.

35:40.225 --> 35:43.228
Collins Avenue walking that
little shiatsu of his

35:43.271 --> 35:45.621
up and down the boardwalk
with a smug face.

35:45.665 --> 35:47.101
It's an embarrassment, frankly.

35:47.145 --> 35:48.015
We can fix that.

35:48.058 --> 35:50.452
Oh, yeah and how's that, Greg?

35:50.496 --> 35:52.454
Even if that money is out there
somewhere,

35:52.498 --> 35:53.977
we don't have the budget
to keep digging holes

35:54.021 --> 35:55.936
to know where to
try to find it.

35:55.979 --> 35:58.591
We're talking about the most
notorious gangster

35:58.634 --> 36:00.114
in American history.

36:00.158 --> 36:02.508
We're just asking
for a little rope.

36:02.551 --> 36:05.641
A little rope, so you two can
hang yourselves, huh?

36:05.685 --> 36:09.167
Andre. Just consider it.

36:11.299 --> 36:14.172
[Keys clicking]

36:15.521 --> 36:18.001
[David muttering]

36:23.268 --> 36:24.530
[Knocking on door]

36:27.750 --> 36:29.709
Hey, hey.

36:29.752 --> 36:31.363
Hi.

36:31.406 --> 36:35.236
I was, um, I was
in the neighborhood.

36:35.280 --> 36:37.978
Come in, come in, yeah.

36:39.893 --> 36:46.247
So I was about to take a break,
so we need some glasses.

36:46.291 --> 36:48.293
I've only got these glasses
so let me fix something.

36:48.336 --> 36:49.337
One second.

36:49.381 --> 36:51.252
[Maureen laughs]

36:57.345 --> 36:59.347
How is the book going?

36:59.391 --> 37:00.261
- DAVID: The book?
- Yeah.

37:00.305 --> 37:02.959
DAVID:
Uh, struggling.

37:03.003 --> 37:05.440
I'm guessing that's a good
thing, you know?

37:10.532 --> 37:12.273
Is this the guy you are writing
the book about?

37:12.317 --> 37:13.361
Yeah.

37:17.060 --> 37:18.584
Meyer Lansky?

37:18.627 --> 37:22.065
That's him. Here, sit down.

37:22.109 --> 37:23.328
Should I know who that is?

37:23.371 --> 37:26.156
Uh, he ran a lot of Casinos.

37:26.200 --> 37:28.942
So, if you're into gambling,
I guess, but, um.

37:28.985 --> 37:30.596
Hey, I'm so sorry
about the mess.

37:30.639 --> 37:32.424
Oh stop, I don't care.

37:36.341 --> 37:39.387
That's my daughter.
She's really cheeky.

37:39.431 --> 37:41.128
And looks a lot like me.

37:41.171 --> 37:43.957
Oh, she's pretty cute.

37:44.000 --> 37:49.049
Yeah, and I got a picture
of my son somewhere,

37:49.092 --> 37:51.138
but of 18 months.

37:51.181 --> 37:52.400
He looks like a bug.

37:55.098 --> 37:58.145
But uh, here you go,
and don't worry, you know?

37:58.188 --> 37:59.538
- Yeah, I noticed.
- Yeah, okay.

37:59.581 --> 38:00.495
